(Base56 Address Encoding) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Status: Alpha documentation snapshot \(2026-03-12\).) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This note explains why Atho uses Base56 for addresses instead of Base58 or other alphabets.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Why Base56) Tj
T*
(- **Ambiguity reduction:** Drops lookalike characters to cut down on copy/paste and) Tj
T*
(transcription errors.) Tj
T*
(- **Human-friendly:** Better readability in CLI, logs, and printed/exported materials; fewer) Tj
T*
(mistakes when reading aloud or over screenshares.) Tj
T*
(- **Consistent casing:** One unambiguous alphabet across all components \(CLI, API responses,) Tj
T*
(wallet UI\) so there is one canonical representation.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(How it?s built) Tj
T*
(- HPK \(hashed public key\) is derived from the Falcon public key \(SHA3-384\).) Tj
T*
(- HPK bytes are encoded with the Base56 alphabet \(digits/letters chosen to avoid lookalikes\).) Tj
T*
(- Decoding reverses the process to recover the HPK for validation and address matching.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Characters removed \(6\) and why) Tj
T*
(Removed from the larger Base62 set because they are visually confusing:) Tj
T*
(- O \(uppercase O\) ? looks like zero) Tj
T*
(- 0 \(zero\) ? looks like letter O) Tj
T*
(- I \(uppercase i\) ? looks like l/1) Tj
T*
(- l \(lowercase L\) ? looks like I/1) Tj
T*
(- 1 \(one\) ? looks like I/l) Tj
T*
(- i \(lowercase i\) ? too similar to I/l) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Atho Base56 alphabet \(safe set\)) Tj
T*
(Uppercase: A B C D E F G H J K L M N P Q R S T U V W X Y Z) Tj
T*
(Lowercase: a b c d e f g h j k m n p q r s t u v w x y z) Tj
T*
(Digits: 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Benefits of removing lookalikes) Tj
T*
(- Avoids misreading addresses and wrong transfers) Tj
T*
(- Reduces fraudulent lookalike addresses) Tj
T*
(- Cuts typing errors on mobile and across fonts/screen sizes) Tj
T*
(- Mirrors the rationale of Base58 and other error-resistant encodings) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Why not Base58 or Bech32?) Tj
T*
(- Base58 still includes ambiguous glyphs for some fonts/locales; Base56 removes more of them.) Tj
T*
(- Bech32 adds checksums and HRPs, but is longer; Atho prioritizes shorter, readable strings with) Tj
T*
(a controlled alphabet. A checksum can be layered separately if desired.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Security: encoding vs. strength) Tj
T*
(- Base56 is purely an encoding choice for human readability; it does not reduce cryptographic) Tj
T*
(strength. The underlying security comes from Falcon-512 signatures and SHA3-384 hashing of) Tj
T*
(public keys.) Tj
T*
(- SHA3-384 offers a larger digest than SHA-256, providing stronger collision resistance and) Tj
T*
(headroom against preimage/collision attacks; the Base56 text is just a view of those bytes.) Tj
T*
(- Collusion/lookalike resistance: by removing ambiguous characters and using explicit network) Tj
T*
(prefixes, it?s harder to trick users with visually similar addresses, while the HPK \(SHA3-384\)) Tj
T*
ET
endstream
endobj
